# web-ui-prototypes / tldraw

tldraw is a React infinite-canvas SDK. The deterministic source-of-truth is a `.tldr` document — a JSON serialization of the tldraw store (shapes, pages, bindings) that is diffable and version-controllable. The headless deliverable is an SVG (or rasterized PNG) exported via `@kitschpatrol/tldraw-cli`, which serves a local tldraw instance and drives Puppeteer to invoke the SDK's export.

controls do
  web-ui-prototypes.title: { label: "Title", type: "text" }
  web-ui-prototypes.format: { label: "Format", type: "select", options: ["svg", "png"] }
  web-ui-prototypes.tldr: { label: "tldraw snapshot (.tldr)", type: "textarea", file: "src/drawing.tldr" }
end

## Required reading
- tldraw llms.txt docs (official, tldraw.dev docs license): https://tldraw.dev/llms.txt — plus llms-docs.txt, llms-examples.txt, llms-releases.txt
- Official Claude Code plugin tracking issue (official, MIT): https://github.com/tldraw/tldraw/issues/8107 — public plugin not yet shipped as of mid-2026
- Tldraw SDK Documentation Writer (community, unstated license): https://mcpmarket.com/tools/skills/tldraw-sdk-documentation-writer
- `@kitschpatrol/tldraw-cli` (MIT, by Eric Mika) — the headless export path

## Render
```bash
npm i -g @kitschpatrol/tldraw-cli   # Node 18+, Chromium auto-downloaded by puppeteer
npx @kitschpatrol/tldraw-cli export ./out/drawing.tldr --format svg -o ./out -n drawing
# PNG variant: --format png  → writes ./out/drawing.png
```

## Failure modes
- Headless rendering is NOT pure Node — tldraw export depends on a browser DOM. The CLI spins headless Chromium; ensure puppeteer's Chromium downloaded (~1-2s startup per export).
- Custom shapes must implement a `toSvg` method or they will not appear in the SVG export.
- `.tldr` schema is versioned (SDK 5.x, May 2026); a snapshot authored against a much older/newer schema may need migration before export.
- `Editor.toImage()` / `getSvgElement()` from the SDK are unsuitable for this headless pipeline without the same browser dependency — use the CLI.
